testimonials_short:
One thing that's negatively
affected me...is not being
able to engage in the
therapeutic support that I had
before. I was going to be re-
assessed…and since I'm not
'urgent', that's not going to
happen.

My mental health has been
severely affected by the
lockdown.

I am struggling to work from
home, maintain my
relationship, keep my home,
and be a superwoman. It’s hard
not to break

I...haven’t seen family or
friends since lockdown as I
live alone so my mental health
has drastically declined in
the past two months.

I am experiencing relatively
extreme mood swings and it
feels harder to manage my
emotions.

I feel anxious about other
issues that are being ignored,
and that the government is
saying just to use common
sense, which is subjective and
a lot of people are not
following the rules anyway.

It’s hard working from home,
exhausting. And whilst it’s
nice to spend time going for
walks, I’d rather be getting
on with my life but the future
is so unknown

I have enjoyed the time to
slow down and think more and
I’ve realised that my
lifestyle will change after
lockdown.

Every day is like an emotional
rollercoaster. I'm absolutely
fine and grateful one day, and
the next depressed and wish
life would be normal again

I struggle a bit with anxiety
and social anxiety, being at
home has increased this on the
basis I’m not out everyday
building resistance to this
struggle.

Just because people aren’t
pensioners doesn’t mean
they’re not vulnerable. Living
alone has been incredibly
difficult and I’m not someone
that has ever experienced
issues surrounding my mental
health.

I've lost the daily
distractions that really help
to keep my mental health
afloat

It has led to a lot of time to
think about past traumatic
experiences that I had been
able to mask and push to the
back of my mind, using
everyday life and distraction
as a coping mechanism.

My family is in another
country and I wish I could
visit as I miss them very
much.

I have had time to slow my
life down & evaluate where I
spend my time. I didn't
realise how much I needed to
do this. I feel grateful for
the small things & have
reconneted with my partner, we
had nearly split up before
this.

I worry about the impact of
protective gear on my ability
to communicate with others
because I am deaf.

Whilst the situation has given
me more time at home as a
family unit which I have
loved, I have adjusted my
working hours to ensure I
can...balance my husband's
working hours and childcare.
This juggle has been quite a
strain at times.

I have been feeling a little
panicky about coming out of
the lockdown as I have found
it difficult to get a clear
picture of the advice given.

I have differing days - some
seem to be bright and positive
and others much more negative
with a lot of anxiety.

I feel a lot more relaxed
spending time at home.

What I have found more
stressful is the virtual
pressures of needing to stay
connected. It's actually been
more difficult for me to find
moments of peace. It's also
been harder to jusify taking
time off.

My husband works 12+ hour days
in London so it’s been
wonderful having him work from
home ie eat with myself and
the children.
